when membrane potential is -20 mV","It results in simultaneous sodium and potassium ion inward current","It causes increased potassium ion efflux"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe funny current (If), also known as the pacemaker current, plays a crucial role in the spontaneous depolarisation of cardiac pacemaker cells. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt results in simultaneous sodium and potassium ion inward current\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. The funny current is a mixed cation current that allows both sodium and potassium ions to flow into the cell, contributing to gradual depolarisation during the pacemaker potential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt stimulates spontaneous repolarisation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The funny current actually contributes to spontaneous depolarisation, not repolarisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt allows entry of chloride ions into the cell\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The funny current involves sodium and potassium ions, not chloride ions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt activates when membrane potential is -20 mV\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Funny channels typically open at more negative (hyperpolarised) potentials, around -60 mV to -40 mV.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt causes increased potassium ion efflux\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The funny current involves an inward (into the cell) movement of ions, not an efflux of potassium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe funny current is essential for the automaticity of cardiac pacemaker cells, particularly in the sinoatrial node. It activates upon hyperpolarisation and contributes to the slow diastolic depolarisation phase of the action potential in these cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The funny current (If) is a mixed sodium-potassium inward current that contributes to spontaneous depolarisation in cardiac pacemaker cells.","Funny channels open at hyperpolarised membrane potentials (around -60 mV) and close at depolarised potentials.","The funny current is crucial for the automaticity of the sinoatrial node and other cardiac pacemaker tissues."],"references":["DiFrancesco D. The role of the funny current in pacemaker activity. Circ Res. 2010 Feb 19;106(3):434-46. doi: 10.1161/CIRCRESAHA.109.208041. PMID: 20167941.","Tortora, G. J., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Cooke, J., Di Pietro, F., Diversi, T., ... \u0026 Summers, S.. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 3rd Asia-Pacific Edition. 2022. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","DiFrancesco D, Borer JS. The funny current: cellular basis for the control of heart rate. Drugs. 2007;67 Suppl 2:15-24. doi: 10.2165/00003495-200767002-00003. PMID: 17999560."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45543"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14436"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45543"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-10T10:02:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-10T10:03:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7131"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60123"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"40","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/40"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading"